SIMPLE: mackerel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mackerel
<hw>Mack"er*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>maquerel</ets>, F. <ets>maquereau</ets>, fr. D. <ets>makelaar</ets>
mediator, agent, fr. <ets>makelen</ets> to act as agent.]</ety> <def>A
pimp; also, a bawd.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackerel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mackerel
<hw>Mack`er*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>maquerel</ets>, F. <ets>maquereau</ets> (LL.
<ets>macarellus</ets>), prob. for <ets>maclereau</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>macula</ets> a spot, in allusion to the markings on the fish. See
<er>Mail</er> armor.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of the
genus <gen>Scomber</gen> of the family <fam>Scombridae</fam>, and of
several related genera. They are finely formed and very active oceanic
fishes. Most of them are highly prized for food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The common mackerel (<spn>Scomber scombrus</spn>), which
inhabits both sides of the North Atlantic, is one of the most important
food fishes. It is mottled with green and blue. The Spanish mackerel
(<spn>Scomberomorus maculatus</spn>), of the American coast, is covered
with bright yellow circular spots.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Bull mackerel</b></col>, <col><b>Chub
mackerel</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Chub</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Frigate mackerel</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Frigate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Horse mackerel</b></col> . <cd>See
under <er>Horse</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel bird</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the wryneck; -- so called because it arrives in
England at the time when mackerel are in season.</cd> --
<col><b>Mackerel cock</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the Manx
shearwater; -- so called because it precedes the appearance of the
mackerel on the east coast of Ireland.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel
guide</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Garfish</er>
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel gull</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<cd>any one of several species of gull which feed upon or follow
mackerel, as the kittiwake.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel midge</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very small oceanic gadoid fish of the North
Atlantic. It is about an inch and a half long and has four barbels on
the upper jaw. It is now considered the young of the genus
<gen>Onos</gen>, or <gen>Motella</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel
plow</b></col>, <cd>an instrument for creasing the sides of lean
mackerel to improve their appearance.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> --
<col><b>Mackerel shark</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
porbeagle.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mackerel sky</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Mackerel-back sky</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a sky flecked with small
white clouds; a cirro-cumulus. See <er>Cloud</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mackerel sky</qex> and mare's-tails⟦br⟧
Make tall ships carry low sails.</q> <rj><qau>Old Rhyme.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mackerel shad</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>mackerel scad</ent>⟦br⟧
